This is the simple touch screen interface that I designed:
The design includes button layouts of the left-hand side of the screen and an information section
on the right side of the screen.
The Buttons
For my design, I decided to represent six floors. The buttons aligned vertically to represent the
corresponding floor levels. A “help” button also exists if the user needs any assistance.
For my design, I tried to minimize the number of buttons to reduce complexity and make it easier
for the users to utilize the functionalities of the elevator.
Feedback
When the user selects a button, the button is highlighted, and a sound is played. Doing so allows
the user to receive feedback from their action and make it easier to understand which floors the
elevator will eventually navigate to. Additionally, the right side of the screen serves as an
informational section and displays the current floor of the elevator, the action the elevator is
performing, and a simple graphic to represent the current action of the elevator.

Elevator Evaluation
Image of the elevator interface that I am evaluating:
Gif of elevator interface that I am evaluating:
This image of an elevator interface was taken at 25Twenty apartment complex.
The control interface design is simplistic; however, the floor numbers are
arranged side to side which can be a bit confusing to understand at first. The
elevator also has 3 other buttons. Two for opening and closing the door, and
another to serve as an emergency button. The buttons used to open and close the
door are represented by graphics that may seem difficult interpret. Using words
would be a better alternative.
 Common Uses of Elevator
o Navigate quickly to a different floor; either up or down.
o Force elevator to open doors.
 Rare Uses of Elevator
o Force elevator doors to close.
o Signal an emergency.
o Call for help.
 The elevator that I am examining allows for both these common and rare uses to take
place relatively easily.
In order to get the elevator to move to a particular floor, the user simply needs to press a
numbered button. The button layout is a bit unintuitive but can quickly be understood. Once a
floor is selected, the elevator will begin to move up or down. The elevator also provides a braille
interface to aid those with visual disabilities. When a button is pressed, the elevator provides
feedback by lighting up the button and playing a sound. Due to the layout of the elevator buttons,
selecting the wrong floor is an easy mistake to make. The only suggestion I could make to
improve the design is to align the elevator floor buttons vertically. That way, its easier to
understand how to navigate the building floors.
